<DOC><DOCNO> AP890721-0203 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 0145EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-EEC-Soviets     07-21 0187</FIRST><SECOND>PM-EEC-Soviets,0194</SECOND><UNK>EEC Opens Talks on Trade Pact with Soviet Union</UNK><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The European Economic Community says ithad opened talks with the Soviet Union on a trade and economiccooperation agreement.   The two sides discussed trade, investment and economiccooperation, the EEC's executive commission said Thursday. Afurther round of talks is expected in early October.   Frans Andriessen, EEC commissioner for External Relations, saidin June the 12-nation trade bloc wanted to conclude a 10-yearagreement, which would not offer any trade concessions to theSoviet Union, but would include ``most favored nation'' treatmentunder international trade rules.   The accord also would offer management training and jointventures as well as cooperation on the environment, energy andnuclear safety.   The EEC had a trade deficit of $2.9 billion with the SovietUnion in 1988. The EEC imports mainly natural gas and petroleumproducts from the Soviet Union while it exports mainly manufacturedproducts and machinery.   The EEC has signed trade and cooperation agreements withCzechoslovakia and Hungary, is close to signing a pact with Poland,and has opened negotiations with East Germany.</TEXT></DOC>